499
00:30:13,054 --> 00:30:14,074
In terms of the toolset,

500
00:30:15,435 --> 00:30:16,395
okay, so I think, you know,

501
00:30:18,015 --> 00:30:22,196
it's important when you're making the game to be able to throw stuff away

502
00:30:23,137 --> 00:30:24,477
and to change stuff really fast.

503
00:30:26,417 --> 00:30:29,318
For a better blob, we could kind of do that, but we couldn't do it fast enough.

504
00:30:31,018 --> 00:30:33,139
We were using our own proprietary engine.

505
00:30:34,657 --> 00:30:38,862
And so there was a lot of thinking about how to change our development process to be faster.

506
00:30:39,462 --> 00:30:43,186
We considered changing to maybe some other middleware engine,

507
00:30:43,887 --> 00:30:48,372
but moved away from that after considering the advantages that we'd received from

508
00:30:48,912 --> 00:30:53,056
our own engine in terms of portability, like we were able to do a launch title on Vita as a result of our

509
00:30:53,841 --> 00:30:54,521
our own engine,

510
00:30:55,641 --> 00:30:57,162
just sort of the independence that it brings.

511
00:30:57,722 --> 00:30:59,383
Instead, what we did is we focused on making

512
00:30:59,423 --> 00:31:02,425
a lot of incremental changes in a lot of different places

513
00:31:03,105 --> 00:31:04,786
with a couple examples to follow,

514
00:31:05,346 --> 00:31:08,067
with the key kind of thrust being that

515
00:31:09,408 --> 00:31:10,969
we wanted to make an attitude change

516
00:31:12,169 --> 00:31:13,910
where people would kind of reflect more

517
00:31:14,190 --> 00:31:15,731
on how efficient their process was

518
00:31:15,851 --> 00:31:18,172
and look for ways to simplify what they were doing.

519
00:31:20,594 --> 00:31:21,354
So problem one...

520
00:31:23,477 --> 00:31:25,097
we made, I hope it's visible, yeah.

521
00:31:25,237 --> 00:31:27,658
So the collision hulls for about a blob,

522
00:31:28,338 --> 00:31:31,279
they had to be made extremely precisely and smoothly

523
00:31:31,519 --> 00:31:32,719
because the blob is a blob

524
00:31:32,919 --> 00:31:34,560
and it needs to not get caught up on corners.

525
00:31:35,080 --> 00:31:37,581
And that takes a lot of time for designers to do.

526
00:31:38,001 --> 00:31:39,201
As you can see, the game world there,

527
00:31:39,221 --> 00:31:40,642
you can see exactly what you're looking at

528
00:31:40,662 --> 00:31:42,342
or you have some idea, oh, here's a gear

529
00:31:42,422 --> 00:31:44,803
and here's a crusher or something.

530
00:31:45,963 --> 00:31:48,984
The art team would import this stuff in a 3D Studio Max.

531
00:31:50,136 --> 00:31:51,877
But they couldn't use that stuff in Max.

532
00:31:52,017 --> 00:31:53,658
They just, they had to use it as a guide

533
00:31:54,098 --> 00:31:54,779
for what they would make.

534
00:31:55,139 --> 00:31:57,621
And so the iteration process was slow and painful.

535
00:32:00,863 --> 00:32:03,064
So we switched from this kind of curvy whole stuff

536
00:32:03,145 --> 00:32:05,726
to a rectilinear style, more a traditional platformer style.

537
00:32:06,227 --> 00:32:07,948
So the designers could plop down blocks.

538
00:32:08,268 --> 00:32:10,309
We didn't remove the ability to do the custom work.

539
00:32:11,058 --> 00:32:13,798
but it was just kind of a process thing that generally they didn't use it.

540
00:32:14,879 --> 00:32:15,479
And the artists,

541
00:32:15,999 --> 00:32:17,839
they were able to import these hulls

542
00:32:18,440 --> 00:32:22,701
as flat geometry and just use it as geometry in 3D Studio and apply textures

543
00:32:22,761 --> 00:32:25,241
on top of it so we could very quickly get something

544
00:32:25,841 --> 00:32:27,422
vaguely passable into the game.

545
00:32:27,922 --> 00:32:31,743
And when there were changes to the level geometry, it wasn't that big a deal to fix it.

546
00:32:33,133 --> 00:32:36,775
A similar problem, in A Better Blob we had pretty weak visual effects.

547
00:32:38,415 --> 00:32:45,217
We went to a PAX and we sat beside Retrograde, which if you're familiar with that game, has

548
00:32:45,437 --> 00:32:46,857
an enormous number of effects.

549
00:32:47,818 --> 00:32:52,599
And it was just depressing to see how far off we were from another indie developer.

550
00:32:54,817 --> 00:32:58,459
Our visual system, our effects system was visual driven.

551
00:32:58,539 --> 00:33:03,522
So it was intended for the artists to be able to use these visual tools to make their effects.

552
00:33:04,202 --> 00:33:08,825
But in practice, the artists didn't, I don't know, like it or it just wasn't good enough.

553
00:33:09,225 --> 00:33:10,966
And the designers ended up making all the effects.

554
00:33:11,387 --> 00:33:13,688
And then those effects, you know, I mean, they're not artists.

555
00:33:13,708 --> 00:33:15,569
The artists are going to be better at that kind of stuff.

556
00:33:15,609 --> 00:33:16,350
So it wasn't great.

557
00:33:18,004 --> 00:33:21,146
So after thinking about it for a while, first we thought, well, maybe we'll make the tools better.

558
00:33:21,546 --> 00:33:24,367
But that's expensive. It's hard. It's a difficult problem.

559
00:33:24,608 --> 00:33:28,610
So instead, we flipped it around completely, and we said, you know, we're not going to make the tools better for the artists.

560
00:33:29,090 --> 00:33:31,211
What we're going to do is we're going to make the tools better for the programmers,

561
00:33:31,271 --> 00:33:32,972
and we're going to let the programmers drive the effects.

562
00:33:33,612 --> 00:33:38,057
So we made changes to the engines so that we could put shaders into the engine much more easily and quickly.

563
00:33:38,077 --> 00:33:40,280
That you could make more changes on the fly.

564
00:33:40,300 --> 00:33:46,547
And we added a system so that the programmers could easily put handles on their shaders so that the artists could tune the shaders.

565
00:33:46,887 --> 00:33:51,492
So we changed into this process where it was actually the programmers driving the initial effects.

566
00:33:51,953 --> 00:33:55,416
Like, oh, I think we should have smoke here, or a waterfall, or something like that.

567
00:33:56,212 --> 00:34:00,217
we would make these prototype effects, add handles to them, and then the artists would tune them.

568
00:34:00,597 --> 00:34:03,801
So they wouldn't make the effects, but they would refine the effects.

569
00:34:04,582 --> 00:34:07,866
Make them arty. Make them just way better than the programmers could do.

570
00:34:11,410 --> 00:34:14,694
Finally, I'll talk sort of quickly about the target platform.

571
00:34:16,098 --> 00:34:18,481
We released our previous games on PS3 and PS Vita.

572
00:34:18,962 --> 00:34:21,124
Our first about a blob was a pub fun game,

573
00:34:21,144 --> 00:34:22,446
which means you get like a,

574
00:34:22,486 --> 00:34:24,508
there's like an advance against royalties arrangement,

575
00:34:25,029 --> 00:34:26,871
but you get paid after the project ships.

576
00:34:27,032 --> 00:34:29,354
So you have to be able to finance the project to that point.

577
00:34:31,377 --> 00:34:32,919
For Guacamelee!, we decided, you know what,

578
00:34:32,959 --> 00:34:35,261
we're gonna just reevaluate everything.

579
00:34:36,284 --> 00:34:37,885
The change was, there was no change.

580
00:34:38,125 --> 00:34:39,547
We ended up doing exactly the same thing.

581
00:34:40,127 --> 00:34:41,868
But only after a lot of thinking about it,

582
00:34:42,209 --> 00:34:44,470
and talking to people, and looking at all our options.

583
00:34:44,850 --> 00:34:46,612
So I guess you could say there wasn't a change,

584
00:34:46,692 --> 00:34:48,893
exactly, in the outcome, but there was more of a,

585
00:34:50,315 --> 00:34:51,596
a more aggressive change in attitude,

586
00:34:51,636 --> 00:34:53,957
like we have to be very aggressive about,

587
00:34:55,058 --> 00:34:56,559
about questioning our presumptions

588
00:34:56,619 --> 00:34:57,920
about what's the right thing for us to do.

589
00:35:00,212 --> 00:35:02,713
So, just some brief logic for why we ended up doing what we did.

590
00:35:02,733 --> 00:35:05,535
Why in consoles? Because we have experience there.

591
00:35:05,796 --> 00:35:07,837
Because there's some barriers to entry there,

592
00:35:07,997 --> 00:35:10,859
and so if you can get over those barriers, it's good for you as a developer.

593
00:35:12,880 --> 00:35:14,341
Why PSN? Why self-publish?

594
00:35:16,383 --> 00:35:16,723
We have...

595
00:35:17,324 --> 00:35:21,006
The studio is in a position to largely or entirely self-finance the game,

596
00:35:21,106 --> 00:35:22,027
so we didn't need a publisher.

597
00:35:23,705 --> 00:35:26,007
We've had some bad experiences of our own with publishers

598
00:35:26,027 --> 00:35:27,809
when we were working on retail games.

599
00:35:28,510 --> 00:35:30,131
A couple of us worked on a project where

600
00:35:31,012 --> 00:35:32,213
a game that was supposed to be a port

601
00:35:32,694 --> 00:35:34,515
was, for marketing reasons, labeled as a sequel,

602
00:35:35,236 --> 00:35:36,777
which meant that the team was crushed under work

603
00:35:37,158 --> 00:35:37,558
and it was...

604
00:35:38,379 --> 00:35:41,321
it felt like it was impossible for the game to get a good review.

605
00:35:43,695 --> 00:35:45,516
Another experience was one of the other founders.

606
00:35:46,057 --> 00:35:47,458
He worked on retail games for PC.

607
00:35:47,498 --> 00:35:48,658
Worked on a retail game for PC.

608
00:35:48,678 --> 00:35:49,739
They had a publishing deal.

609
00:35:49,779 --> 00:35:50,680
The game was on the shelves.

610
00:35:51,040 --> 00:35:51,740
The game was selling.

611
00:35:52,261 --> 00:35:54,542
The publisher simply refused to give them any royalties.

612
00:35:56,423 --> 00:35:57,404
So we were afraid of that.

613
00:35:57,644 --> 00:35:58,965
But we talked to publishers all the time.

614
00:35:59,205 --> 00:36:01,066
And for every project, we tried to pitch it to publishers

615
00:36:01,486 --> 00:36:03,327
in the hopes that maybe there could be an arrangement,

616
00:36:03,427 --> 00:36:04,828
something that would make sense for both sides,

617
00:36:05,168 --> 00:36:06,609
but also because they see a lot of games.

618
00:36:06,989 --> 00:36:08,190
And so we would show them the game,

619
00:36:08,510 --> 00:36:10,391
and we would just try to gauge or read between the lines

620
00:36:10,431 --> 00:36:11,052
in their feedback.

621
00:36:11,820 --> 00:36:17,027
They see a lot of pitches. We're trying to leverage that experience for our own benefit.

622
00:36:18,909 --> 00:36:20,612
So we talked to Sony about PubFund early.

623
00:36:21,693 --> 00:36:22,374
They made an offer.

624
00:36:23,696 --> 00:36:25,438
Wasn't quite what we were hoping for.

625
00:36:26,251 --> 00:36:28,432
We showed the game publicly, it got a great response.

626
00:36:28,773 --> 00:36:32,255
We started talking to publishers, we were very close to signing with a publisher.

627
00:36:32,795 --> 00:36:36,218
And then Sony came back and gave us a slightly different offer for the PubFund.

628
00:36:36,638 --> 00:36:38,539
And because of our good working relationship with them,

629
00:36:39,100 --> 00:36:41,121
because we had actually had good trust with them,

630
00:36:41,301 --> 00:36:42,862
we knew that there weren't going to be shenanigans.

631
00:36:44,243 --> 00:36:46,905
And because philosophically the company,

632
00:36:46,925 --> 00:36:48,986
founders are conservative financially,

633
00:36:49,387 --> 00:36:52,689
we were very concerned about our minimum return rather than maximizing our return.

634
00:36:53,309 --> 00:36:54,810
It seemed like a great deal for us, so we did it.

635
00:36:56,901 --> 00:37:00,603
So to summarize, we had key team members attach the project

636
00:37:01,284 --> 00:37:05,266
day-to-day like key founders with a strong vision in place,

637
00:37:05,947 --> 00:37:08,148
and so we could focus on building the pieces one by one.

638
00:37:08,728 --> 00:37:11,130
We used external deadlines to drive the development,

639
00:37:11,630 --> 00:37:12,851
and that dovetailed with the marketing,

640
00:37:12,871 --> 00:37:14,111
which I'll talk about next,

641
00:37:14,632 --> 00:37:16,613
and we showed all our milestones externally.

642
00:37:17,914 --> 00:37:20,195
We became more free with letting ideas into the game,

643
00:37:21,316 --> 00:37:24,298
trying to pursue, pull out the personality of the team.

644
00:37:25,341 --> 00:37:27,202
and off-the-cuff stuff was taken seriously,

645
00:37:28,023 --> 00:37:29,504
but also vetted by the producer.

646
00:37:30,845 --> 00:37:33,866
We kept our existing engine, but we focused changes in places

647
00:37:33,906 --> 00:37:35,608
where there were productivity issues.

648
00:37:35,648 --> 00:37:37,509
So instead of making the engine more complicated,

649
00:37:38,449 --> 00:37:40,451
we looked at ways of simplifying our processes

650
00:37:40,491 --> 00:37:41,571
or making things more efficient.

651
00:37:43,012 --> 00:37:45,154
And finally, yeah, we went through the same

652
00:37:45,174 --> 00:37:46,174
distribution channel again,

653
00:37:47,976 --> 00:37:49,697
but only after a lot of thought.

654
00:37:50,817 --> 00:37:53,139
It was useful for us to explore all our options again.

655
00:37:57,164 --> 00:37:58,125
Okay, so into the marketing.

656
00:37:58,145 --> 00:38:03,390
I'll talk a bit about how we chose to change, how we revealed the game,

657
00:38:04,210 --> 00:38:06,132
relationship with marketing in general,

658
00:38:06,152 --> 00:38:09,875
uh, and attitude change with respect to launching the game.

659
00:38:11,457 --> 00:38:14,880
So with Aboda Blob, it just seemed like nobody knew that the game existed

660
00:38:15,380 --> 00:38:15,981
when it came out.

661
00:38:16,001 --> 00:38:18,403
Uh, like, when an article would go up,

662
00:38:19,124 --> 00:38:21,646
uh, the comments would suggest that most people had never heard of the game.

663
00:38:22,620 --> 00:38:28,067
You could tell that because they would engage in a flame war about how the game was clearly ripped off from GISH.

664
00:38:29,869 --> 00:38:33,774
There was just low anticipation, and there were very few day one reviews.

665
00:38:35,917 --> 00:38:37,920
We were very precious with About a Blob.

666
00:38:38,524 --> 00:38:42,107
We were scared to show it frequently or in an early state

667
00:38:42,167 --> 00:38:46,791
because we were scared that things might change and it would somehow confuse people out there.

668
00:38:47,771 --> 00:38:50,374
We were concerned about polish, that it wasn't to a high enough standard.

669
00:38:50,834 --> 00:38:53,336
So for Guacamelee!, because that obviously didn't work,

670
00:38:54,097 --> 00:38:55,838
we just said, okay, we're just going to put it out there the whole time.

671
00:38:56,119 --> 00:38:58,601
We're not going to hide it. We're going to put things out pretty early.

672
00:39:00,262 --> 00:39:02,004
So because the deadlines were based around showings...

673
00:39:03,263 --> 00:39:05,525
we kind of frequently had these things that we could show.

674
00:39:05,985 --> 00:39:06,745
We announced the game,

675
00:39:07,385 --> 00:39:09,626
not even when we were fully out of pre-production,

676
00:39:10,067 --> 00:39:12,168
and thereafter we just tried to attend any public shows

677
00:39:12,188 --> 00:39:13,048
that we possibly could.

678
00:39:13,548 --> 00:39:15,669
Went to PAX, we had presence at GameCom,

679
00:39:15,949 --> 00:39:18,390
we went to E3, fortunately we got an Indicade,

680
00:39:18,410 --> 00:39:21,112
we were at GDC, but we would also do local shows.

681
00:39:22,432 --> 00:39:24,473
In Toronto, in New York, in London,

682
00:39:24,553 --> 00:39:25,854
people would sometimes email and say,

683
00:39:25,874 --> 00:39:27,155
hey, we think your art is cool,

684
00:39:27,415 --> 00:39:29,356
could your game be at our event?

685
00:39:29,416 --> 00:39:31,396
And we're like, sure, here's a build, just send the build in.

686
00:39:33,317 --> 00:39:38,240
We first revealed around IGF 2011 with an announcement trailer.

687
00:39:38,280 --> 00:39:40,122
And like I said, we were just exiting pre-production.

688
00:39:40,922 --> 00:39:41,843
So why reveal then?

689
00:39:43,083 --> 00:39:44,544
We had something we thought was interesting.

690
00:39:45,725 --> 00:39:46,745
We were committed to the game.

691
00:39:47,606 --> 00:39:49,807
And it also helped put pressure on the team to deliver.

692
00:39:50,388 --> 00:39:52,329
So I'm just going to show the announcement trailer

693
00:39:53,690 --> 00:39:56,952
to give you some idea, if you can remember the old video,

694
00:39:58,252 --> 00:40:00,834
sort of how early, comparatively early this is.

695
00:42:04,375 --> 00:42:06,616
So yeah, I don't know about, I don't know what you guys see.

696
00:42:06,636 --> 00:42:08,336
I, I, it looks awful.

697
00:42:09,116 --> 00:42:10,937
Uh, this is all I see.

698
00:42:11,537 --> 00:42:13,778
It looks, the environments look bad.

699
00:42:13,798 --> 00:42:16,098
I see all sorts of gameplay problems,

700
00:42:16,358 --> 00:42:17,658
jerking of the camera, stuff like that.

701
00:42:18,499 --> 00:42:20,379
The point is to say, I, I don't know what you see.

702
00:42:21,159 --> 00:42:23,280
Uh, is that we felt nervous about it.

703
00:42:23,720 --> 00:42:25,200
We forced ourselves to put it out anyway.

704
00:42:26,241 --> 00:42:27,261
And as you can see also, we kind of,

705
00:42:27,561 --> 00:42:29,501
we used part of the concept video at the beginning there.

706
00:42:29,801 --> 00:42:30,582
Kind of reusing stuff.

707
00:42:33,809 --> 00:42:37,730
For a Better Blob, the quality of coverage from media outlets was pretty bad.

708
00:42:38,230 --> 00:42:41,252
We did all our own marketing on the first game. We were extremely green.

709
00:42:42,212 --> 00:42:45,273
We were not sure how to do things, or in what order to do things,

710
00:42:45,493 --> 00:42:48,854
or even what good results would look like or should look like.

711
00:42:49,315 --> 00:42:51,916
But we saw other independent developers doing it themselves,

712
00:42:51,956 --> 00:42:54,657
and so we thought, oh, well, naturally we should do it ourselves.

713
00:42:55,577 --> 00:42:57,598
And in retrospect, that was not a good idea.

714
00:42:58,858 --> 00:43:01,479
In part because we don't really have, especially at the time,

715
00:43:01,499 --> 00:43:02,400
we didn't really have good...

716
00:43:03,117 --> 00:43:05,858
personalities on the team for pitching the game ourselves.

717
00:43:07,798 --> 00:43:09,398
So we hired a PR firm

718
00:43:10,699 --> 00:43:11,639
near the end of a,

719
00:43:12,019 --> 00:43:12,919
there were like three projects,

720
00:43:12,959 --> 00:43:14,879
About a Blob, Mutant Blobs Attack, and then Guacamelee.

721
00:43:14,899 --> 00:43:17,160
We hired a PR firm near the end of Mutant Blobs Attack.

722
00:43:17,800 --> 00:43:20,040
And we did that because we went to a PAX

723
00:43:20,560 --> 00:43:22,381
and there was another indie game in front of us

724
00:43:23,581 --> 00:43:26,242
which is sort of similar kind of game in a lot of ways.

725
00:43:26,782 --> 00:43:28,762
And we noticed that they were getting a huge amount of press

726
00:43:28,822 --> 00:43:29,562
attending their booth.

727
00:43:30,262 --> 00:43:33,084
And we went up and we talked to them and we looked at what they were doing

728
00:43:33,104 --> 00:43:36,225
and it turned out that they were kind of signed on with some small publisher

729
00:43:36,265 --> 00:43:39,887
and the publisher had hired a PR firm and the PR firm was just bringing all these media people

730
00:43:40,628 --> 00:43:42,549
to the booth and so we realized we were...

731
00:43:42,569 --> 00:43:45,710
we were being idiots.

732
00:43:49,195 --> 00:43:53,699
So yeah, we worked with a PR firm basically throughout the entirety of Guacamelee's production.

733
00:43:53,759 --> 00:43:57,142
I mean, not in a continuous flow, but like every time there was going to be some kind of event,

734
00:43:57,202 --> 00:43:58,684
we would get back in touch and work with them.

735
00:43:59,264 --> 00:44:02,527
So they helped us arrange stuff with the trade shows and do key announcements.

736
00:44:02,547 --> 00:44:05,570
They organized meetings, advised on approach, timing.

737
00:44:06,210 --> 00:44:07,912
They helped us later with our press tour.

738
00:44:07,992 --> 00:44:09,493
They facilitated relationships.

739
00:44:09,553 --> 00:44:13,777
They just, it's like, basically, it's, I mean, it's obvious, but it's a job.

740
00:44:13,797 --> 00:44:15,539
There's a reason why people have a job doing this.

741
00:44:16,375 --> 00:44:17,937
They know something if they've been doing it.

742
00:44:18,037 --> 00:44:18,758
We know nothing.

743
00:44:18,938 --> 00:44:21,361
So we should try to work with somebody who knows something

744
00:44:21,401 --> 00:44:21,922
in order to learn.

745
00:44:24,586 --> 00:44:25,847
Finally, the launch.

746
00:44:26,768 --> 00:44:28,030
The launch also went very poorly.

747
00:44:29,232 --> 00:44:30,433
There were basically no previews.

748
00:44:31,850 --> 00:44:34,092
The review camp, the Metacritic review camp wasn't too bad

749
00:44:34,452 --> 00:44:35,673
for a small indie game.

750
00:44:36,313 --> 00:44:37,474
But a lot of them came in late.

751
00:44:38,675 --> 00:44:40,476
Not great store placement, although it wasn't terrible

752
00:44:40,636 --> 00:44:42,177
because we were in pub fun, Sony was supportive.

753
00:44:43,058 --> 00:44:44,699
And we were crushed under other games.

754
00:44:45,079 --> 00:44:46,320
Stacking released the same day.

755
00:44:46,960 --> 00:44:48,641
Plants vs. Zombies released the same day.

756
00:44:49,382 --> 00:44:51,323
Bionic Commando 2 released one week before.

757
00:44:51,703 --> 00:44:53,244
There was another indie game called Explodemon

758
00:44:53,264 --> 00:44:54,125
that released the same day.

759
00:44:54,725 --> 00:44:55,986
And we didn't know that.

760
00:44:56,026 --> 00:44:58,968
We didn't know that that was happening until a week before.

761
00:44:59,953 --> 00:45:01,635
And then, when we heard that, we were like,

762
00:45:02,135 --> 00:45:04,716
oh, okay, well, should we change?

763
00:45:05,577 --> 00:45:07,738
Uh, you know, and we're like, uh, I don't think, uh,

764
00:45:08,119 --> 00:45:09,059
you know, it's too much effort.

765
00:45:12,661 --> 00:45:13,402
So, the change?

766
00:45:14,022 --> 00:45:16,484
I mean, not one change, just sort of waking up.

767
00:45:17,404 --> 00:45:20,006
Um, we took the launch extremely seriously

768
00:45:20,306 --> 00:45:22,227
for Guacamelee!, we planned it long in advance.

769
00:45:22,448 --> 00:45:23,388
There are many differences.

770
00:45:25,325 --> 00:45:30,369
We did a proper press tour multiple weeks before, so we had a proper preview build that we could leave with people.

771
00:45:31,390 --> 00:45:35,933
We attended a lot of trade shows near the launch, so we could get coverage. We were fortunate to be in the IGF.

772
00:45:37,134 --> 00:45:40,176
But we went to GDC and we were in the Sony booth. We were at PAX East.

773
00:45:40,857 --> 00:45:45,120
We had some award nominations around that time, so we got kind of coverage from that.

774
00:45:46,260 --> 00:45:48,702
But because we planned it properly, we had proper previews.

775
00:45:50,399 --> 00:45:56,502
and proper reviews. The PR firm helped us set a proper embargo date. We had an exclusive

776
00:45:56,562 --> 00:46:06,505
review, which meant that we had great placement. That was on IGN. We had excellent store placement,

777
00:46:06,586 --> 00:46:10,707
thanks to Sony. We worked closely with Sony on this. We talked to them, tried to figure

778
00:46:10,787 --> 00:46:13,848
out when is a good time, when are there not going to be games coming out.

779
00:46:15,172 --> 00:46:18,513
We even moved our dates around because we realized that there was another indie game,

780
00:46:18,553 --> 00:46:22,654
that was Monaco, was coming out when we planned to come out.

781
00:46:23,834 --> 00:46:25,975
And we talked to them and said, oh, maybe there's a problem.

782
00:46:26,355 --> 00:46:28,255
They weren't worried about it, but we were very worried about it,

783
00:46:28,335 --> 00:46:29,455
so we just moved our dates back.

784
00:46:31,416 --> 00:46:36,357
So I guess overall you could say, as I say, not one thing, just everything.

785
00:46:36,897 --> 00:46:38,518
Like, this is a serious issue.

786
00:46:39,698 --> 00:46:41,138
We were, yeah, very naive initially.

787
00:46:42,418 --> 00:46:46,080
So to summarize, we put the game out there into the world constantly.

788
00:46:46,120 --> 00:46:49,142
We didn't hide it, and we let it change as we went and didn't worry about that.

789
00:46:49,442 --> 00:46:53,304
Because it was more important to kind of create awareness, especially for a small title like ours.

790
00:46:54,144 --> 00:46:57,406
We accepted that we needed help, so we hired a PR firm.

791
00:46:58,346 --> 00:47:00,567
In a way, that's like, it's kind of an ego thing, right?

792
00:47:00,847 --> 00:47:02,168
Like, I can do it, we're indie.

793
00:47:02,888 --> 00:47:03,509
We can do anything.

794
00:47:05,169 --> 00:47:05,810
But, we can't.

795
00:47:07,574 --> 00:47:13,277
And finally we took the launch extremely seriously, whereas we hadn't, you know, you're at the end of the project, you're exhausted.

796
00:47:13,617 --> 00:47:16,238
It's just such a big deal to even finish a game and get it done.

797
00:47:18,479 --> 00:47:22,881
We changed our point of view, like, it's not done until three or four months after the game is released.

798
00:47:26,703 --> 00:47:27,383
So, wrapping up.

799
00:47:28,906 --> 00:47:32,067
The results, well, I mean, I'm doing the talk because the results were good.

800
00:47:32,968 --> 00:47:37,890
The game was a success, it was well-received, it got stronger views, it sold well,

801
00:47:38,490 --> 00:47:42,132
we continue to release it, it's going to come out soon on additional platforms.

802
00:47:43,452 --> 00:47:47,634
Basically, it just eclipses our first game in almost every single way.

803
00:47:51,315 --> 00:47:55,537
A few, sorry, a few takeaway concepts, generalities.

804
00:47:57,698 --> 00:48:02,161
On the concept side, I think having a clear vision for the game was absolutely critical for us.

805
00:48:02,961 --> 00:48:04,042
It informed what we made.

806
00:48:04,622 --> 00:48:07,364
It determined how people responded to the game after first hearing about it,

807
00:48:07,404 --> 00:48:09,025
because we'd worked on a good initial concept.

808
00:48:09,626 --> 00:48:14,689
And having that tight vision gave us this guidepost that just made the development flow.

809
00:48:15,970 --> 00:48:20,273
On the development side, there are a lot of things to pick on, or to pick from.

810
00:48:20,293 --> 00:48:22,714
But probably the most important was...

811
00:48:24,093 --> 00:48:27,515
our attempts to more aggressively pursue simplicity and focus.

812
00:48:28,336 --> 00:48:31,697
Sort of trying to be more efficient about what we did meant simplifying things,

813
00:48:32,037 --> 00:48:34,459
cutting things, focusing on the most important elements.

814
00:48:35,219 --> 00:48:38,040
Which is scary, especially coming from retail, because in retail,

815
00:48:38,160 --> 00:48:40,562
there's this kind of, there's this psychology which is like,

816
00:48:40,882 --> 00:48:42,843
in order to compete with other retail games,

817
00:48:43,423 --> 00:48:45,364
we have to just put more stuff in.

818
00:48:45,524 --> 00:48:48,966
It has to have this, it has to have online multiplayer, it has to have these things.

819
00:48:50,095 --> 00:48:50,155
uh...

820
00:48:50,596 --> 00:48:51,356
and what we kind of

821
00:48:52,096 --> 00:48:55,937
slowly realizes that's totally wrong particularly for download only games

822
00:48:57,458 --> 00:49:00,539
and finally in the marketing just you know the term always on

823
00:49:01,559 --> 00:49:04,080
instead of doing something or doing something that we did at the end

824
00:49:05,120 --> 00:49:07,801
it was something that we were always doing something we're having weekly

825
00:49:07,841 --> 00:49:08,461
meetings about

826
00:49:08,481 --> 00:49:10,982
that we took seriously throughout the entire development

827
00:49:14,103 --> 00:49:14,503
so that's it

828
00:49:25,903 --> 00:49:28,285
If you have any questions, yeah, I'd be happy to answer them.

829
00:49:28,305 --> 00:49:29,605
I think we have about 10 minutes.

830
00:49:30,746 --> 00:49:31,486
Yep.

831
00:49:31,687 --> 00:49:32,347
Thank you very much.

832
00:49:32,467 --> 00:49:33,187
Very inspiring.

