00:52:12,178 --> 00:52:15,661
I think, you know, so there's there were sort of three key founders, myself and two other guys.

885
00:52:16,521 --> 00:52:18,723
And we all like the Guacamelee thing.

886
00:52:19,716 --> 00:52:22,337
But I had another idea and I was pissed off that we weren't going with my idea.

887
00:52:24,558 --> 00:52:26,819
But I didn't get pissed off for very long,

888
00:52:27,020 --> 00:52:30,181
because it's like, when the rest of the team obviously likes it,

889
00:52:30,321 --> 00:52:33,183
then what do you, you know, why are you holding on to your ego?

890
00:52:33,743 --> 00:52:36,764
And I think that's the thing with the three of us.

891
00:52:37,265 --> 00:52:39,906
We all have slightly different personalities, you know,

892
00:52:39,986 --> 00:52:41,987
and so then there's members on the team who are very,

893
00:52:42,127 --> 00:52:44,728
or of the three founders, there's like one guy who's the most ego-less.

894
00:52:45,974 --> 00:52:49,658
and sort of then because he's there and he's ego-less, it pushes your ego down.

895
00:52:49,918 --> 00:52:52,341
So you're like, you know, we need to be practical, we need to be honest.

896
00:52:53,062 --> 00:52:55,605
So yeah, so yeah, that kind of, that does happen.

897
00:52:55,866 --> 00:52:59,210
But at the end of the day, I mean, we kind of take the attitude of, you know,

898
00:52:59,710 --> 00:53:04,356
if everybody likes it and I'm not so sure, then maybe I should be going with everybody.

